snippet.textDisplay:
I just wanted to take a moment and appreciate your willingness to be open about your opinions and so many things people will censor themselves on because they don't want to risk losing subscribers or people in general not liking them because of being "controversial".

In your videos, you talk so casually and candidly about sex&sexuality, social and psychological issues, periods and the experience of being a woman, feeling lonely or disoriented, depressed, confused, unsure, insecure, scared, intimidated, all feelings that although you often make them into self-deprecating jokes, you also address them in a serious fashion, in little talks with us, and I really appreciate it.

I couldn't be that brave with such a large audience and with the pressure of being liked being part of you making a living, so I really want to take a moment and appreciate your willingness to be that open and vulnerable, it really means a lot to me to see it-it inspires me to be more comfortable, confident, and assertive myself, more honest with myself and unapologetic, and sometimes I absorb your attitude just through watching you.
I don't think you'll see this comment and it doesn't really matter if you don't. It's just something I felt needed to be said. Thank you! :)

snippet.textDisplay: Ashley I’d like to suggest that you listen (in order) to the podcast called Beat Your Genes which is about something called evolutionary psychology— which sheds incredible light on personalities and social dynamics based on two evolutionary drivers. It views all kinds of social situations from the filters of those drivers. It also involves analyzing personality across 5 categories and that is also hugely enlightening.  The technical quality is bad in the first episodes but it gets better and the content is fascinating and it explains SO MUCH about male-female dynamics, friendship dynamics, etc.  As you settle into your new life in NYC I think you’ll be glad for this perspective.  I am interested to know what you think about it.

snippet.textDisplay:
when you move to ny HAVE A MEETUP!!! watching/listening to you is just basically going through the conversations i have with myself in a day LOL

also other stuff: Aesthetics wise, you should look out for battery park and the bethesda terrace and a lot more that I won't spam with but yeah! dig deep lol.
- honestly i keep on talking about how i wanna ditch new york, but i cant imagine being anywhere else. just being on the subway (especially the 7 train during sunset) is so therapeutic in a sense that you mean absolutely nothing to the people around you yet are part of what creates such a desired, unique culture.
- you'll learn to have a love hate relationship with the mta which any true new yorker will understand when you walk in late and drenched saying "i hate the mta". and you'll know you've become a new yorker when you've fallen asleep and just magically woken up on your stop. plus the sentences "a subway caught on fire" or "someone jumped onto the tracks" become normal on an unhealthy level but also nobody cares
- also as an urban dancer pls pls pls check out the shows and competitions because it is an whole sub-culture that you can't find anywhere else
- thriftings a hit or miss here which im sure you maybe know by now? best ones are downtown(try cure thrift shop near 14th union square&ofc L-train vintage) and brooklyn
- biking along brooklyn pier, blasting kinda sad love pop music while its drizzling also hits on a whole diff level: best way to enhance single vibez
